Challenge 01: Sauce Packets

CLEANING UP THE

MESS OF FAST FOOD SAUCES

Developing a bio-based, yet cost-effective alternative for highly disposable condiment packets.

Please read below for more information on desired expertise and R&D priorities.

  • * Sheet lamination

    * Extrusion lamination

    Products shall have at least 20% bio-based content. Product shall be labelled plastic mono-material with at least 90% being made from one single plastic

    Product shall have good printability

  • Product/material of the layer in contact with the liquid shall be approved for food contact (EU / US)

Challenge 02: Rigid Bottles

KEEPING OUR SKIN (AND OUR PLANET) LOOKING FRESH.

Optimising the recyclability of rigid cosmetics bottles.

Please read below for more information on desired expertise and R&D priorities.

  • * Polymer extrusion

    * Polymer formulation

    * Injection molding

    * Thermoforming

    Product shall be made from thermoplastics

    Plastics shall not be crosslinked

    Product shall be labelled plastic mono-material with at least 90% being made from one single plastic

  • Product shall have excellent barrier performance (OTR<1 and WVTR<1 at 38°C and 90% RH). Products shall be able to stand on a shelf and be easily handled by a customer.

  • Product shall not contain prohibited additives according to EU regulations

Challenge 03: Milk Cartons

TAKING ALT-MILK PACKAGING TO GREENER GRAZING.

Redefining liquid paperboard packaging as a mono-material.

Please read below for more information on desired expertise and R&D priorities.

  • * Sheet lamination

    * Extrusion lamination

    * Metallization of plastics

    All plastics used in the multilayer packaging shall be either biodegradable or made from renewable resources. The plastic in contact with the liquid shall have aseptic features. A replacement for aluminum foil as the element conferring oxygen resistance is highly welcome. Materials and product design shall be selected in a way that does not inhibit the recyclability of the finished material in the paper recycling streams. The material giving structural integrity is paperboard with a grammage approximately between 280-300 g/m². Paperboard is preferably made out of recycled fibers provided that they don’t interfere with the food contact requirements (EU / US)

  • Product shall withstand low temperatures (4-6 °C) and high relative humidity RH (>90%) without mechanical failure nor loss of shape. Product shall be excellent barrier against moisture and oxygen at 4 °C and 90% RH and 23 °C and 90% RH. Product shall have a good tensile strength and puncture resistance. Products shall be able to stand on a shelf and be easily handled by a customer.

  • Products shall have good printability. Product shall be approved for food contact (EU / US)

  • * Sheet lamination

    * Extrusion lamination

    * Metallization of plastics

    * Paper packaging

    * Food contact requirements

    * Mechanical performance

    * Barrier performance
